article.headline: Nash has 14 assists; six Mavs score in double figs
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks have put together a five-game winning streak, though they're not trying to convince themselves that it's anything special. After all, four of those victories have come against sub-.500 teams. Michael Finley scored 24 points, Dirk Nowitzki added 23 and the Mavericks beat the lottery-bound Seattle SuperSonics on Tuesday night, 118-108. During this successful stretch, Dallas' only win over a playoff team came against Sacramento, and the Kings were without key players Brad Miller and Bobby Jackson. Antawn Jamison had 17 points, Marquis Daniels added 16 points and Steve Nash contributed 14 points and 14 assists to help Dallas improve to 34-5 at home. "I think it's a little misleading," Nash said. "It's not a true indicator of where we are. We're definitely capable, but this has come so easy for us. It won't be easy for us once the playoffs start." The Mavericks continued to excel offensively with small lineups that have included 6-foot-9 forward Antoine Walker logging extensive minutes at center. Dallas scored 118 or more points for the sixth consecutive game. "It was a great effort," Nowitzki said. "We got a lot of fast break and second-chance opportunities. Everything was working offensively." Mavericks coach Don Nelson kept centers Shawn Bradley, Danny Fortson and Scott Williams on the bench for most of the first three quarters. Bradley entered the game late in the third quarter and had eight points and five rebounds in 10 minutes. Few teams have been successful in the playoffs using "small ball" lineups, but the Mavericks feel they have the weapons to buck that trend. "I hope so, because that's what we're going with," Finley said. "If we score the ball and scrap on defense and make the other team work on offense, the scheme can work for us." Brent Barry and Ray Allen had 20 points each for Seattle. Ex-Maverick Ansu Sesay matched a career high with 19 points and set a career high with 10 rebounds for the SuperSonics, who've lost five of six. Ronald Murray had 11 points and a career-best 11 assists for Seattle. Seattle played the second half without second-leading scorer Rashard Lewis, who sustained a left hip flexor and bruised left knee when he slipped on a wet spot on the floor while trying to make a cut in the second quarter. Lewis, who was averaging 18.1 points and 6.7 rebounds, finished with four points and didn't have a rebound in 13 minutes. Lewis said he will test his leg prior to Wednesday night's game at San Antonio. "I'll just see how I feel tomorrow," Lewis said. "I'll warm up and get treatment before the game and go from there." The Sonics took their only lead of the game, 74-73, on Murray's drive with 3:14 left in the third quarter. Nash hit layups on consecutive possessions for a 77-74 lead. Dallas had a 16-5 run over the final 3:14 of the third quarter, capped by Nash's layup with 0.7 seconds left, and grabbed an 89-79 advantage heading into the final quarter. "It happened so fast," Barry said of the Mavericks' run. "The fans saw it, but it was a blur to us." Seattle opened the fourth quarter with three straight 3-pointers, two by Richie Frahm, to pull to 93-88. But the Mavericks answered with an 11-0 run, with nine points from Finley, for a 104-88 lead with 7:21 left. The Mavericks surged to a 22-11 start, connecting on seven straight field goal attempts during one stretch. Meanwhile, the Sonics were missing eight in a row while the Mavericks were building a 34-21 lead heading into the second quarter. Daniels and Nowitzki had 10 points each in the opening quarter. Dallas' run-and-gun offense was dominant in the first quarter as the Mavericks held an 18-0 edge in fast-break points. The Mavericks held a 58-51 halftime edge.

Game notes
The Sonics have lost four straight to the Mavericks. ...Nash has double-doubles in eight of his last 12 games. He's averaging 16.8 points and 11.9 assists over that span. ...Dallas is 16-4 this season when scoring 30 or more points in the first quarter. ...The Mavericks converted all 17 free throw attempts, going without a miss from the line for the second time this season.
